#)Steps to Create a Custom Exception in Java

1)Extend the Exception class (or RuntimeException)
2)If you want a checked exception, extend Exception.
3)If you want an unchecked exception, extend RuntimeException.

#)Define constructors
Usually, you define at least a constructor that accepts a message.
Throw it using throw in your code

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#)Custom Checked Exception Example

üëâ Checked exceptions are those that the compiler forces you to handle using try-catch or throws.

‚úÖ Example: AgeNotValidException (Checked Exception)
// Step 1: Create a custom checked exception
class AgeNotValidException extends Exception {
    public AgeNotValidException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

// Step 2: Use it in a class
public class CheckedCustomExceptionDemo {
    static void checkAge(int age) throws AgeNotValidException {
        if (age < 18) {
            throw new AgeNotValidException("Age must be 18 or older!");
        } else {
            System.out.println("You are eligible to vote!");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            checkAge(15);
        } catch (AgeNotValidException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught Exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}


Output:

Caught Exception: Age must be 18 or older!

üß† Explanation:

AgeNotValidException extends Exception, so it‚Äôs checked.

The checkAge() method declares the exception with throws.

The main() method handles it with try-catch.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Custom Unchecked Exception Example

üëâ Unchecked exceptions (Runtime exceptions) are not checked by the compiler.
You can throw them directly ‚Äî no need for throws or try-catch.

‚úÖ Example: InvalidScoreException (Unchecked Exception)
// Step 1: Create a custom unchecked exception
class InvalidScoreException extends RuntimeException {
    public InvalidScoreException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

// Step 2: Use it in a class
public class UncheckedCustomExceptionDemo {
    static void checkScore(int score) {
        if (score < 0 || score > 100) {
            throw new InvalidScoreException("Score must be between 0 and 100!");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Valid Score: " + score);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        checkScore(120); // This will throw an unchecked exception
        System.out.println("Program continues..."); // won't execute
    }
}


Output:

Exception in thread "main" InvalidScoreException: Score must be between 0 and 100!

üß† Explanation:

InvalidScoreException extends RuntimeException, so it‚Äôs unchecked.

The compiler does not force handling.

The program terminates unless you catch it manually.





----------------------------------------------------------------
 #)Can you explain a few exception handling best practices?
‚ÄúI always make sure to catch only specific exceptions and log them properly instead of swallowing them silently.
I use try-with-resources to close files or database connections automatically.
I never use exceptions for normal logic, and if needed, I rethrow or wrap them with a clear message.
Also, I prefer using custom exceptions for business logic to make the code more meaningful.‚Äù

